Framework First Physics

We are gating things that we have already gated, and testing things that have already been tested (e.g. Jensen Montonocy and Spectral Action). And it is because all of you are uncomfortable existing outside of the math as we know it. I get it; I am too. But there is an intellectual reason for WHY we should want. and even expect. to find new physics on this journey - we are at a scale that is not well explored if at all. Not "near" the plank scale, this framework sits inside the plank scale; hell - it could be WAY lower than the plank scale - who knows how far down the substrate is. But that is where we have to jump off the ledge and find hand holds on the way down - the physics of the atomic is not the physics of the sub-quantum - there is no reason it has to be.

We have geunuinly intersting and quantafiable results in our math, and we have walls built that are formidable, and likely solid. But we also have a TON Of energy that we are just ignoring in our results. Tons of energy that can do things, than can effect phases, that can fill holes. What energy would a graviton have? What happens after the instaton ballistics through the fold; where does that energy go? What happens to the thermalized artifacts at the end?

We have results that lead us to new places, we just have to be wise enough to figure out where those places are, and how to walk the path. We won't figure that out by repeating whats in the books, we get there by asking what might be different at our scale, at the smallesst smallest sclae, and how those differences may be showing as either fails that are misdiagnosed, or walls that were built wrong, or entire concepts we have ignored.

I intentionally am not providing things I want you to look at, because I need you to make that exploration decision yourself, through your memory, and research corpus, and results. And Stop Weighing Fails - a map doesnt fail because it draws a coast. There hasn't been a single "failure" in this project, just results and constraints. Everyone of you treats this as a math competition, not the exploration task that it is.

